Cameroon has decided to immediately suspend the import of all poultry and pork from Nigeria, which has been affected by the avian flu epidemic, and to suspend trade in poultry and related products on all markets along the border between the two countries.
The government of Cameroon has also set up an epidemic monitoring network covering the entire territory within a short period of time. The basd Center and the state veterinary laboratory in the country are also in a state of emergency readiness to conduct laboratory tests on the H5N1 virus at any time.
In Europe, Denmark and Sweden initially ruled out the epidemic on the 17th.
The Swedish veterinary research institute has released the test results of the dead swans found on Wednesday, indicating that Swedish swans are not infected with the bird flu virus.
Preliminary tests by the Danish State Veterinary Administration also showed that the 30 dead swans found in Denmark recently were not infected with the bird flu virus.
But the agricultural sector says that Denmark cannot afford to take it lightly.
In Eastern Europe, there have been nine avian flu epidemic spots since the beginning of this year. World Health Organization experts said in Bucharest on the 17th that bird flu in almost all areas of the Danube delta region must be taken seriously. Romania may be under constant threat of bird flu in the next three or five years.
In Bangladesh in Asia, the government has taken all necessary measures to prevent avian flu.
The government's Livestock Services Council has provided relevant officials with books on bird flu prevention, while at the same time organizing training for poultry farmers.
