Dalai's special envoy held a closed-door meeting with Chinese officials
The Dalai Lama stressed that he hoped for Tibet's autonomy and not independence.
The special envoy of the Tibetan spiritual leader, the Dalai Lama, is holding a closed-door meeting with Chinese officials in Beijing, and the details have not been announced.
This is the fifth formal meeting since the resumption of contacts between the governments of China and the Dalai in 2002.
However, as in the past, the two sides held meetings behind closed doors and the details were not disclosed.
The reporter said that the two sides have held numerous talks, but no substantial results have been achieved so far.
The Dalai Lama, who was in exile in northern India, said that he hoped for Tibet's autonomy rather than independence.
The Chinese side refused to comment on the talks between the two sides.
However, analysts say Beijing hopes the dialogue between the two sides will be due in part to concerns that if the 70-year-old spiritual leader dies, this may lead to a rise in Tibetans' dissatisfaction with the Chinese rule.
Cultural identity
The delegation of the Dalai's government in exile was led by Gallo Lozhu, who was also the chief representative of the previous rounds of talks.
A spokesman for the Tibetan government said that the talks between them and Chinese officials in Switzerland in 2005 were very "close and candid," which brought hope to Tibetans.
The spokesman said that their ultimate hope is to resolve the related problems with the Chinese leadership in accordance with the basis of negotiations, so that Tibetans can have freedom and maintain the cultural identity that they consider to be important.
CGP Pui
The special envoy of the Dalai Lama reiterated that he would not seek independence from Tibet.
