Prior to the visit of the Tibetan spiritual leader, the Dalai Lama, to the United States on 8 November, his special envoy said that the Tibetan government in exile did not demand the independence of Tibet.
Zhu Rongji said in Washington that he hoped the Chinese government would really protect Tibet's unique culture and traditions.
It is expected that during his visit to the United States next week, the Dalai Lama will discuss the Tibet issue with President Bush and hope that Bush will urge the Chinese government to give Tibet genuine autonomy.
The representatives of the Dalai and Beijing officials made direct contacts in Berne for the first time in July this year.
